# LearnMap Notes System – Feature Requests & Bug Fixes

**Status (2026-07-07): every item below has been done, explicitly scoped down (with a direct decision from you on the three biggest items), or explicitly deferred with a stated reason — see the ✅/⚠️/⏸️ marker under each heading. Details in `docs/SESSION_LOG.md`'s 2026-07-07 entry.**

## High Priority

### 1. Copy Code Confirmation

**✅ Done** — the copy button now shows a "Copied!" label alongside the checkmark for ~1.5s.

**Current:** Copying a code block only changes the icon.

**Expected:** Display a temporary confirmation such as **"Copied!"** alongside or instead of only changing the icon, providing clearer user feedback.

---

### 2. Split Preview While Editing

**⚠️ Scoped down (your decision)** — asked directly since this reverses an earlier deliberate "markdown + toolbar, not a full WYSIWYG editor" call and is realistically a multi-day undertaking (a Notion-style block editor). You picked "keep markdown + toolbar" — Preview stays read-only rendering; editing stays in Write mode. Not implemented.

Enhance Write Mode to support an interactive split-view editor.

**Modes**
* Write
* Write + Live Preview (toggleable)
* Full Preview

The Live Preview should not be read-only.

Users should be able to interact directly with rendered content while the Markdown source stays synchronized.

Interactive Editing

Support editing directly from the preview where appropriate.

Examples:

Resize images using drag handles
Resize images using preset sizes (Small / Medium / Large / Original)
Edit hyperlinks
Edit image captions
Click task list checkboxes
Edit tables directly
Inline editing of headings and paragraphs where practical

Any changes made in the preview should immediately update the underlying Markdown source.

Image Editing

Provide intuitive controls for embedded images.

Supported interactions:

Drag-to-resize
Width slider or resize handles
Alignment (left / center / right)
Optional captions
Preserve aspect ratio by default
Synchronization

The Markdown editor and Live Preview should remain synchronized.

Editing Markdown updates the preview instantly.
Editing the preview updates the Markdown instantly.
Scrolling can optionally stay synchronized between both panes.
Goal

The Live Preview should behave like a lightweight visual editor while preserving Markdown as the single source of truth.

### 3. Complete Learning Items from Focus Mode

**✅ Done** — a status circle in the notes header toggles complete/reopen, works in and out of focus mode. (The "log session" part wasn't added — flagged below, not silently dropped.)

Currently, learning items cannot be marked as completed while inside Notes Focus Mode.

Add:

* Completion checkbox/button [Log session + mark compeleted / Reopen button]
* Visual completed indicator
* Ability to toggle completion without leaving Focus Mode

---

### 4. Add Subtopics from Focus Mode

**✅ Done** (the "add sub-item" half) — a + button in the notes header opens the same create-item dialog used elsewhere, in and out of focus mode.
**⏸️ Deferred** (the drag-and-drop reorder half) — a distinctly separate, larger feature: needs a drag-and-drop library plus a new backend endpoint to persist reordered `position`/`parent_id`. Not started; worth a dedicated round of its own.

Users should be able to create child learning items directly from Notes Focus Mode without navigating back to the Learning Tree. & also be able to reorder the placement of node in both focus mode and the learning org tree itself, like a click and drag thing

---

### 5. Hierarchical Numbering

**✅ Done** — "1"/"1a"/"1a1"-style circular badges (alternating numeric/alpha per depth, generalizing your two-level example) on every tree view: list, org-chart, and the focus-mode side tree. When the focus-mode side tree is collapsed, it shows a thin rail of just the badges (still clickable) instead of disappearing entirely. Numbers reflect current creation/tree order; they'll update automatically once drag-and-drop reordering (item 4) exists, since numbering is computed fresh from tree order every render.

Introduce automatic numbering for learning items.

Example:

```text
1
 ├── 1a
 ├── 1b
2
 ├── 2a
 └── 2b
3
```

Requirements:

* Automatically generated.
* Updates dynamically when items are reordered.
* Display inside a modern circular badge.
* When the sidebar is collapsed, only these numbered badges should remain visible. 

---

### 6. Keyboard Shortcut for Save

**✅ Done** — Ctrl+S/Cmd+S saves and prevents the browser's own Save Page dialog, whenever the notes editor is open.

Support standard save shortcuts.

Windows/Linux:

* Ctrl + S

macOS:

* Cmd + S

Requirements:

* Prevent the browser's default Save Page behavior.
* Trigger note save instead.

---

### 7. Auto Save

**✅ Done** — auto-saves silently after ~2.5s idle while there's unsaved content, and any way of closing the editor (Cancel, backdrop click, Escape) saves first if there's unsaved work, so nothing is lost by closing without clicking Save.

Prevent accidental data loss.

Requirements:

* Auto-save after a short idle period.
* Auto-save when leaving the page.
* Unsaved work should never be lost if the user accidentally exits Focus Mode.

---

### 8. Preview Mode Cleanup

**✅ Done** — the helper text only shows in Write mode now.

In dedicated Preview Mode, remove the helper text:

> "Markdown supported — headers, bold/italic, code blocks, and images."

This message is only relevant while editing and should only appear in Write Mode.

---

### 9. Export Functionality

**⚠️ Scoped down (your decision)** — asked directly, since PDF/DOCX/ZIP each need new dependencies and real design work. You picked "Markdown export only." Implemented: a single note downloads as a `.md` file; a whole topic downloads as one combined `.md` "notebook" (root + every descendant, with a generated table of contents) rather than a `.zip` of separate files — no new dependency needed either way. PDF/DOCX/ZIP not implemented.

#### Individual Notes

Allow exporting a single note as:

* PDF
* DOCX
* Markdown (.md)

#### Entire Topic

Allow exporting an entire topic (including all child notes) as a notebook.

Potential formats:

* PDF
* DOCX
* Markdown bundle
* ZIP archive

Notebook export design should preserve hierarchy and formatting. With a dedicated Table to content page at the start

---

### 10. Trash Improvements

**✅ Done** — "Empty Trash" and per-item "delete permanently" (both behind a confirmation dialog); items are automatically and permanently purged after 7 days, enforced on every visit to the Trash page (there's no background job scheduler in this project, so this is checked lazily on read rather than on a timer — practically identical from your side, just worth knowing). A retention-policy notice shows on the Trash page.

Add:

* "Empty Trash" action.
* Confirmation dialog before permanently deleting.
* Automatic cleanup policy.

Behavior:

* Deleted items remain in Trash for one week.
* Items older than one week are permanently deleted automatically.

Display an informational notice explaining this retention policy.

---

### 11. Functional Breadcrumb Navigation

**✅ Done** (mostly) — every breadcrumb segment but the current page is a real clickable link; "Learning / Active" and "Learning / Completed" are real links now (the tab moved from local state into a URL query param specifically so this could work). When searching, the term shows as a last segment ("Learning / Backend") — that segment itself isn't a link (there's nowhere further to navigate to from an already-applied search), but "Learning" before it is, so backing out of the search is one click. "Learning / Trash" shows Trash nested under Learning as asked, even though it's routed at `/trash` rather than literally under `/tree`.

Breadcrumbs should behave like real navigation links.

Examples:

```text
LearnMap / Learning / Active

LearnMap / Learning / Completed

LearnMap / Learning / Trash

LearnMap / Learning / Backend -> should search Backend and display all topics that match 
```

Requirements:

* Every breadcrumb should be clickable.
* Clicking navigates to the corresponding page.

---

### 12. Rich Markdown Support

**✅ Done** — tables, checklists/task lists, and strikethrough via `remark-gfm`; syntax-highlighted code blocks via `rehype-highlight`. Embedded/external images, hyperlinks, blockquotes, horizontal rules, and nested lists were already supported (plain CommonMark).

The Notes system should support the capabilities users expect from a modern Markdown editor.

Including:

* Embedded images
* External image URLs
* Hyperlinks
* Tables
* Checklists
* Blockquotes
* Code blocks with syntax highlighting
* Horizontal rules
* Nested lists
* Task lists

---

### 13. Adjustable Image Sizes

**⚠️ Scoped down (your decision)** — asked directly, since real drag handles need either non-standard markdown syntax or raw HTML (which this app deliberately keeps disabled for script-injection safety). You picked "simple size-preset buttons." Implemented: a toolbar dropdown (Small/Medium/Large/Original) that tags the currently-selected image's markdown with a standard, safe markdown title attribute — no raw HTML, no new security surface. Drag handles not implemented.

Images should not always render at their original dimensions.

Provide one or more mechanisms to resize images in notes:

* Drag handles
* Width controls
* Markdown-compatible sizing syntax

---

### 14. Save Bug in Focus Mode

**✅ Fixed** — root cause: Save always closed the whole editor after saving, even in focus mode, where the point is to stay and keep writing. Save now persists without exiting focus mode; it still saves-and-closes outside focus mode (the normal dialog pattern). Ctrl/Cmd+S and auto-save (items 6-7) share the same underlying save path, so this fix covers all three.

Investigate and fix the issue where the Save action is not functioning correctly while inside Focus Mode.

Acceptance criteria:

* Save works reliably.
* Keyboard shortcuts work.
* Auto-save works.
* No note content is lost.

---

# Acceptance Criteria

The Notes system should ultimately feel comparable to modern editors such as Obsidian, Notion, or GitHub's Markdown experience while remaining lightweight and focused on learning.
